ues that white evangelicals deployed a Christian brand of colorblindness to protect new investments in whiteness. While black evangelicals used the rhetoric of Christian unity to challenge racism, white evangelicals repurposed this language to silence their black counterparts and retain power, arguing that all were equal in Christ and that Christians should not talk about race.As white evangelicals portrayed movements for racial justice as threats to Christian unity and presented their own racial commitments as fidelity to the gospel, they made Christian colorblindness into a key pillar of America’s religio-racial hierarchy. In the process, they anchored their own identities and shaped the very meaning of whiteness in American society. At once compelling and timely, The Myth of Colorblind Christians exposes how white evangelical communities avoided antiracist action and continue to thrive today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRace relationsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aBill McCartney.  aBilly Graham.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aBlack evangelicals.  aBlack liberation theology.  aBlack power.  aC. Peter Wagner.  aC. Rene Padilla.  aChristian colorblindness.  aChurch Growth Movement.  aChurch segregation.  aCivil Rights Movement.  aClarence Hilliard.  aColorblindness.  aDonald McGavran.  aDonald Trump.  aEvangelical colleges.  aEvangelicalism.  aHigher education.  aHoward Jones.  aIndia.  aIntegration.  aJohn Perkins.  aLausanne.  aPhiladelphia.  aPromise Keepers.  aRacial reconciliation.  aRacism.  aRonald Sider.  aSouthern Baptist Convention.  aTom Skinner.  aWhite evangelicals.  aWh